The most likely cause is that you never set the page's **`BindingContext`** to your ViewModel. Without it, the `{Binding}` expressions have no source to resolve against.

**Fix — set the BindingContext**, e.g. in code-behind:

```csharp
public partial class MyPage : ContentPage
{
    public MyPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
    }
}
```

Or in XAML:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             ...>
    <ContentPage.BindingContext>
        <vm:MyViewModel />
    </ContentPage.BindingContext>
    ...
</ContentPage>
```

**Also verify** that your ViewModel implements `INotifyPropertyChanged` (or inherits `ObservableObject` from the MVVM Toolkit) so the UI updates when property values change after initial binding.
